":"Talcott","married_names":["Rogers","Hope"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST037"}],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM061","landmark_blurb":"Lived here with Walter from 1929 until his death in 1948."}],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"First husband John Rogers died young, 1905","body":"Her first husband John Leete Rogers died in 1905 — sources disagree whether they married in 1902 (FamilySearch) or in October 1905 a week before his death (New York Times). Either way she was widowed quickly, and remarried Walter Ewing Hope in April 1909.","number":1},{"category":"family","header":"Mott Schmidt-designed mansion at 43 East 70th","body":"She lived with Walter Hope at 123 East 80th Street New York and from 1929 at a new Mott B Schmidt-designed mansion at 43 East 70th Street. The Schmidt townhouse remained the family's New York seat through Walter's lifetime.","number":2},{"category":"family","header":"Park Avenue widow after Walter's 1948 death","body":"After Walter Ewing Hope's death in 1948 she sold the East 70th Street mansion to banker Maurice Wertheim and moved to 765 Park Avenue. Wertheim filled the former Hope house with a notable modern French painting collection still associated with the address today.","number":3}],"slug":"florence-hope-1881"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}